article.description:
Nikki Teasley had 17 points to lead the
Washington Mystics to a 96-77 victory over the Charlotte Sting on
Thursday night for their first road win of the season.
article.headline: Mystics beat Sting for first road win of season
article.linkText: Mystics beat Sting for first road win of season
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Alana Beard thought back to the third
quarter and broke into a wide smile.

"I've never seen us dominate like that and the domination came
at the defensive end," Beard said after scoring 15 points Thursday
night as the Washington Mystics beat the Charlotte Sting 96-77 for
their first road win. "We got stop after stop and they turned into
easy scores for us on the offensive end."

Washington scored 35 points in the third quarter, making 13 of
20 shots and limiting the Sting to 17 points. The Mystics broke the
WNBA record for points in a quarter (33) that was tied by
Washington in its home win over Charlotte on Tuesday. This is the
first season the league is using a four-quarter format.

Beard's 3-pointer early in the fourth quarter made it 78-59. The
Mystics, who shot 50 percent, led by as many as 24 points after
that.

Nikki Teasley had 17 points for the Mystics (6-3), who were 0-3
away from the Verizon Center and coming off an 87-70 victory over
the Sting at home Tuesday.

"We're happy to break through and hopefully we'll have more
confidence when we go on the road," Mystics coach Richie Adubato
said.

Monique Currie scored a career-high 22 points and fellow rookie
LaToya Bond added 14 in her first start for the Sting (2-6), who
were outrebounded 40-26 as they played without injured starters
Tammy Sutton-Brown (bruised right knee) and Helen Darling (strained
hamstring).

The 96 points allowed tied a team record set at Utah in 2000.

"You have to understand personnel," Sting coach Muggsy Bogues
said. "For some reason, people keep getting mixed up in what
they're supposed to do. You've got to know who the shooters are.
It's not hard to figure out."

The Sting built a 25-19 lead on Tye'sha Fluker's reverse layup
with 8:25 left in the second quarter. Washington rallied to tie the
score, before the Sting took a 42-38 halftime lead on Sheri Sam's
jumper with 2 seconds left.

The Mystics took advantage of their depth in the second half as
five players scored in double figures despite being without forward
Crystal Robinson for most of the game because of a cramp in her
calf.

"When you shoot 8-for-14 on 3s, you usually win the game,"
Adubato said. "We were really lighting it up in the second half
and they were shorthanded. We caught them pretty good."

Sutton-Brown and Darling were both injured in the first half
Tuesday. Darling is expected to miss about a week, while
Sutton-Brown could play Sunday at Indiana.

Center Janel McCarville, the No. 1 overall pick in the 2005
draft, started in place of Sutton-Brown and finished with a career
high-tying 11 points.

"We can hang with some of the best teams in the league during
the first half, but coming out of halftime something just doesn't
click with us," McCarville said. "We just have to figure out what
it is and eliminate it."
